      <body>
         <listPerson>
            <person xml:id="pers0197">
               <p>Böhler was ordained in <date when="1737-12">Dec. 1737</date>, by <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2310.xml"/>Zinzendorf</persName>, to serve as the
                  Moravian pastor in <placeName>Savannah, Georgia</placeName> and undertake
                  missionary work among the slaves in <placeName>Purrysburg, South
                     Carolina</placeName>. He arrived in <placeName>London</placeName> en route to
                     <placeName>America</placeName> a few days before <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>&apos;s return from
                     <placeName>Savannah</placeName>, and they met on <date when="1738-02-07">Feb.
                     7, 1738</date>. <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName>
                  procured lodgings for Böhler, who in turn instructed <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> in Moravian piety. This
                  culminated in a personal experience of saving faith for <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2176.xml"/>CW</persName> on <date when="1738-05-21">May
                     21</date>,<!-- Assume year as 1738 --> and for <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> on <date when="1738-05-24">May
                     24</date>. By this point Böhler had left <placeName>London</placeName> for
                     <placeName>Georgia</placeName>, but not before he and <persName><ref
                        target="/persons/pers2180.xml"/>JW</persName> founded a new religious
                  society in Fetter Lane, <placeName>London</placeName>, on <date when="1738-05-01"
                     >May 1</date>. During his first visit to <placeName>North America</placeName>,
                  Böhler helped to establish a Moravian settlement in <placeName>Bethlehem,
                     Pennsylvania</placeName>. He returned to <placeName>England</placeName> in
                     <date when="1741">1741</date> and preached for a time in
                     <placeName>Yorkshire</placeName>, but went back to <placeName>North
                     America</placeName> in <date when="1742">1742</date> with a party of German
                  emigrants. In <date when="1744">1744</date> he returned to
                     <placeName>Germany</placeName> where he was consecrated a bishop in <date
                     when="1748">1748</date>. In <date when="1753">1753</date> Böhler went again to
                     <placeName>North America</placeName> and for the next eleven years he divided
                  his time between <placeName>America</placeName> and <placeName>Europe</placeName>.
                  After the death of <persName><ref target="/persons/pers2310.xml"
                     />Zinzendorf</persName>, Böhler returned to <placeName>Europe</placeName>
                  permanently and died in <placeName>London</placeName> from the effects of a stroke
                  in <date when="1775">1775</date>. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 115–16; and
                  Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>, 35.</p>
            </person>
         </listPerson>
      </body>
